In his Piscatory Eclogues Sannazaro proiessed to be playing the part of a pioneer.13 Thus at iv. 17 he writes:

nunc litoream ne despice Musam quam tibi post silvas, post horrida lustra Lycaei (si quid id est) salsas deduxi primus ad undas, ausus inexperta tentare pericula cymba

And in Eleg. iii. 2, 57-58 he has:

quandoquidem salsas descendi ego primus ad undas, ausus inexpertis reddere verba sonis.

This claim ignores certain of the Idyls of Theocritus (vi, xi„ xxi) an author whom Sannazaro knew very well. But it
